<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-16T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-16T03:00:00-05:00" n="8" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d8">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/1372:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-16T11:00:00+03:00">January 16, 1935—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 16—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>19. Japanese Chargé d’Affaires informs me that he has received long and
                            favorable telegraphic instructions from his Government relative to the
                            Chinese Eastern Railway negotiations. He thinks chances are excellent
                            that sale will be consummated within 6 weeks.</p>
                        <p>In reply to a query he categorically denied that there was any substance
                            to current rumors that a nonaggression pact was also probable.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>